1. 145. Some decisive step was necessary now. The Greeks seeing the Romans at their highest point of glory expected every year that they had gone sar enough to provoke the jealousy of the godS‚ and, like their own states in Greece, would fall. The Rhodians began to assert their independence. Antiochus availed himself of the opportunity to seize Egypt. Even the faithful Eumenes’ loyalty was supposed to be wavering. If the republic could not find some year-officer more successful than Philippus, their system stood condemned.
